<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12042n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12042n">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12042n"> 42(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Gratzacham!</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Daire said unto the saint: &lsquo;Lo, this cauldron is thine.&rsquo; And St. Patrick said: &lsquo;<i>Gratzacham</i>.&rsquo; Then Daire returned to his own home and said: &lsquo;The man is a fool, for he said nothing good for a cauldron of three firkins, except &ldquo;<i>Gratzacham&rdquo;.&rsquo; Then Daire <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> said to his servants: &lsquo;Go and bring us back our cauldron.&rsquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Then Daire asked his people, saying: &lsquo;What said the Christian when ye took away the cauldron?&rsquo; But they answered: &lsquo;He said <i>Gratzacham</i> again.&rsquo; Daire <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> said: &lsquo;<i>Gratzacham</i> when I give, &lsquo;Gratzacham</i> when I take away. His saying is so good that with those <i>Gratzachams</i> his cauldron shall be brought back to him.&apos;&rsquo; <small> Very Rev. Dean Kinane, <a name="TKSP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#TKSP"><cite title="source">St. Patrick: his life, his heroic virtues, his labours, and the fruits of his labours</cite></a>, (ed. unknown) 157-8</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Repeated at 219(a) </mm> </dd></dl>
